<TEXT>
the foreman of the oliver north jury says the 
jurors were caught in a war between the democrats and the 
republicans and should have received the testimony of president 
bush and former president reagan 
nevertheless i think it was a fair trial denise anderson 
34 told reporters at a news conference in her living room friday 
24 hours after the jury convicted north of three irancontra 
charges and acquitted him of nine others 
asked whether the trial was fair even though reagan was not 
called to testify about the events that shook his second white 
house term ms anderson said it was fair to a certain degree 
i feel as though reagan and i could go on to elaborate on who 
else should have been down there she said 
she did not elaborate on who else but when asked if she 
included bush she replied im not leaving him out 
asked if she would like to have heard reagans testimony ms 
anderson said yes because he knew a lot about what was going 
on 
both bush and reagan have said they told investigators all they 
knew about the irancontra scandal which occurred while reagan was 
president and bush vice president 
the defense subpoenaed both of them to testify but judge 
gerhardt gesell quashed the subpoena he cited court precedents 
against requiring the testimony of a sitting president and said 
the defense had not shown that reagans testimony was needed 
documents in the trial suggested a bigger role for bush than 
revealed earlier concerning the solicitation of other countries 
support for the contra rebels in nicaragua at a time when us 
military aid for them was banned by law but bush who visited 
honduras president in early 1985 declared thursday the meeting 
had not been part of any deal to provide honduras with expedited 
us aid in return for help for the rebels 
asked whether the trial was worth the money it cost the jury 
foreman said i think in a way it was a waste of taxpayers 
money i think it was a war going on right here in our congress i 
see it as a war between the democrats and the republicans 
at the white house spokesman marlin fitzwater turned away 
questions about a pardon for north saying he asked bush about it 
and the president replied i havent discussed it with anybody 
