<TEXT>
jamalat abu luli shyly pulled 
aside the collar of her tunic to show the mark from her latest 
encounter with the israeli army 
at age 14 she has been shot three times with rubbercoated 
pellets fired by soldiers 
when there is trouble on the streets of the rafah palestinian 
refugee camp someone being arrested or beaten by soldiers 
jamalat joins the crowd that almost inevitably forms to protest 
this is what i have to do it is my duty she said friday 
sitting with her mother brothers and sisters in their house of 
four tiny rooms in the camps shabura quarter 
her latest injury a week earlier left a mark on her skin over 
the right clavicle the doctor at the un relief and works agency 
clinic closed the wound left by the rubbercoated metal pellet with 
two stitches 
i went to the unrwa clinic like i always do she said i 
had an xray but nothing was wrong with the bone 
the clash began when soldiers tried to force a teenage boy to 
climb up a utility poll to remove an outlawed palestinian flag 
jamalat said 
they dragged him out of his house they started to beat him 
of course people came out to help she said adding that 12 
others were hit by the pellets that soldiers fired after tear gas 
failed to chase off the crowd 
in the room where jamalat was interviewed there was a picture 
of her 24yearold brother farid who is serving the third year of 
a fouryear sentence on charges he was a member of the outlawed 
fatah yasser arafats faction of the plo 
there also was a picture of american singer michael jackson and 
a framed saying from islams holy koran god is kindly with his 
people 
jamalat said her best subjects in school are science and math 
and she hopes to be a nurse or doctor but if she gets her dream 
she added id like to be a soldier in the palestine army 
she smiled when asked if she would go out again to take part in 
the next protest of course she said i am not afraid 
jamalat said she was hit the first time in december in the 
right arm when soldiers tried to break up a protest at her junior 
high school three months later two of the pellets struck her 
right thigh as women tried to block an arrest near her home 
she saved one of the rubber bullets from the second clash it is 
a metal ball about the size of a marble covered by hard rubber 
jamalat has never been seriously injured and was never counted 
among the armys list of wounded only those hospitalized with 
wounds from plastic bullets or lead rounds are on that list 
her latest wound came near her house off a dirt street 
alongside the rusted twisted track of the railway that used to run 
from cairo to beirut before it was destroyed in the 1948 
arabisraeli war 
rafah is on the egyptian border and the gaza strip was 
controlled by egypt from 1948 until the strip was captured by 
israel in the 1967 middle east war 
jamalats house is up a lane about two feet wide that runs 
between the walls of the cement block and stucco houses she lives 
there with her mother and father grandmother six brothers and 
three sisters 
her father and mother were born in beersheba but fled when the 
town became part of israel her father travels to work as a farm 
laborer in israel while jamalat stays home to protest 
and what does she want from the protests 
to be free she said to have our own government our own 
flag our own money 
