<TEXT>
five companies have sold wheat to the soviet 
union under the new subsidized grain deal announced by president 
bush 
in all the agriculture department is expected to approve 
subsidies on 15 million metric tons of wheat destined to the 
soviet union the first 300000 tons were announced on friday 
christopher e goldthwait acting general sales manager for the 
departments foreign agricultural service said the sales by five 
exporting companies call for shipment later this month 
goldthwait said the subsidies averaged 846 per ton or about 
23 cents per bushel of wheat the total for the 300000 tons would 
be about 25 million 
the soviet union had bought more than 4 million tons of us 
wheat for 198889 delivery at prices subsidized under the 
departments export enhancement program or eep but the previous 
authorization had virtually run out with the last sale march 13 
bush under pressure from usda and farmstate members of 
congress announced a new authorization on may 2 of 15 million 
tons half of what had been sought however according to wheat 
people and others the soviets agreed to buy an additional 15 
million tons of wheat later in the summer at regular market prices 
members of congress want the bush administration including the 
office of management and budget to clarify the role of the subsidy 
program and to explain why there has been a slowdown in new 
authorizations 
in addition to the wheat usda said the soviet union bought an 
additional 200000 tons of corn for delivery during the current 
marketing year which runs through sept 30 
the latest sales brought to a record 191 million tons the total 
corn and wheat sales to the soviet union for delivery this year 
under terms of the longterm supply agreement between the two 
countries the old mark of 186 million tons shipped to the soviets 
was reached in 198485 
corn which is not subsidized makes up almost 15 million tons 
of the current total with wheat at 413 million tons in addition 
the soviets have bought 450000 tons of soybeans 137 million tons 
of soybean meal and 757400 tons of grain sorghum 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 394 bushels 
of corn or 367 bushels of wheat or soybeans the 300000 tons of 
wheat would be about 11 million bushels and the 200000 tons of 
corn about 79 million bushels 
wheat prices have been averaging about 415 per bushel at the 
farm level according to the latest usda fiveday average meaning 
that the latest sale could have a farm value of around 46 million 
the corn sale at around 256 per bushel would have a current 
farm value of 20 million 
under eep arrangements private exporters can sell us 
commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition 
in selected overseas markets and then collect free government 
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses or subsidies 
goldthwait said the new subsidized wheat sales were handled by 
ferruzzi usa inc 50000 tons central states enterprises inc 
50000 peavey co 120000 union equity exchange 50000 and 
richco grain ltd 30000 
the identities of firms selling corn or other commodities not 
awarded usda subsidies are not disclosed 
