<TEXT>
the bush administration has met with the big 
three automakers to discuss legislation that would help bring about 
commercial production of vehicles that burn methanol and other 
gasoline substitutes 
the head of the environmental protection agencys clean air 
programs william g rosenberg discussed possible legislation in 
late april with the big three automakers 
were giving it serious consideration epa spokesman david 
cohen said friday he said the administration considers the 
technology new and exciting 
the proposals if adopted would be included in president bushs 
draft of broad revisions to the clean air act cohen said 
cohen said that rosenberg in meetings with the automakers 
outlined the benefits of methanol to the environment the 
alcoholbased fuel has been presented as a means of cutting 
emissions of gases that cause smog as well as a way of reducing 
us dependence on foreign oil 
inevitably the point was made that if alternative fuels prove 
to be as effective in terms of their environmental benefits as we 
think they may be it will relieve a bit of the pressure to explore 
other control options cohen said 
the discussions were general and focused only on environmental 
benefits of alternative fuels cohen said 
there has never been any talk about specific emissions 
equipment or reductions cohen said there has never been any 
talk of a time frame 
rosenberg discussed alternate fuels with executives of general 
motors corp ford motor co chrysler corp and the motor vehicle 
manufacturers association a trade group representing the us 
makers cohen said 
gm through spokesman john anderson said the discussions were 
routine part of the normal process of helping policymakers make 
informed decisions 
were not negotiating anderson said were exchanging 
information 
there was no immediate comment friday from ford and chrysler 
the auto industry has been working on alternative fuels 
technology for years but prospects for commercial production have 
been clouded by the lack of a national distribution system for 
methanol and concerns about poor performance and other barriers to 
customer acceptance 
the three major us automakers have produced prototypes of cars 
that can run on a mixture composed mainly of methanol and some of 
the vehicles are capable of switching from methanol to pure 
gasoline 
