<TEXT>
attorney general dick thornburgh is 
threatening to end the american bar associations role in screening 
prospective federal judges unless it agrees not to consider 
political or ideological beliefs 
the abas standing committee on federal judiciary would no 
longer screen prospective nominees unless the bar group keeps a 
commitment that it made to made to thornburgh says david runkel a 
senior aide to the attorney general 
the aba denies it made such a commitment 
as he left the justice department on friday night thornburgh 
said we expect them to honor an agreement to revert to pre1980 
language in the abas judicial screening guidelines 
the 1977 version does not contain any exception to the statement 
that political and ideological views are not considered 
subsequent versions of the guidelines contain an exception that 
such views are considered if they bear on the candidates ability 
to be a fair impartial and openminded judge 
it is this language that thornburgh and others cite as evidence 
that the aba has been using political and ideological views as 
yardsticks for a candidates fitness for the federal bench 
the aba says it never agreed to what thornburgh described in 
testimony tuesday to the house judiciary committee the dispute 
broke out that day when aba leaders took issue with thornburghs 
statement 
the justice department fired back on friday 
runkel said the screening panel would be allowed to resume its 
traditional role of helping the president screen prospective 
judicial candidates as soon as the statement made by the attorney 
general to the house judiciary committee is accepted by the 
aba runkel said 
in a statement friday night aba president robert raven 
reiterated the bar groups position that the federal judicial 
committee does not examine and make value judgments about 
candidates political or ideological views 
problems of wording and problems of perception are curable 
raven said we look forward to working out mutually acceptable 
language with the attorney general 
thorburgh replied they got our language go back to what it 
was in 1979 thats what they agreed to and we expect them to honor 
it 
the issue is especially ticklish for thornburgh because his 
choice for deputy attorney general robert b fiske jr has come 
under fire from some conservative republicans for the role he 
