<TEXT>
when the 1400 soviet soldiers 
stationed in this base 42 miles from berlin pack up and move out 
they will leave with few memories of germany 
from russianlanguage films at the enlisted mens club to 
borzhomi mineral water brought in from soviet georgia the soldiers 
have lived an entirely selfcontained existence and they say 
theyve had virtually no chance to commune with the locals 
the soviets who tinkered with their freshly painted equipment in 
a carefully orchestrated show for foreign journalists friday are 
among the 50000 troops and 5000 tanks the kremlin is withdrawing 
from eastern europe in a disarmament gesture aimed at spurring 
similar concessions from nato 
the hurriedly organized tour of the base that houses the 
vislensky tank regiment comes in advance of the pullouts start on 
may 17 and appeared intended to cast the kremlin in a peacemaking 
role during an internato dispute over the pace and course of 
disarmament 
but the visit for 118 journalists offered a rare glimpse into 
the everyday life of soviet soldiers abroad and confirmed longheld 
beliefs that the lot of these foreignbased fighting men is one of 
isolation and monotony 
asked if enlisted men could spend their free time outside the 
concreteslab walls surrounding barracks bordered by skeletal trees 
killed by acid rain 19yearold vasily yamkovoi replied rarely 
he and others said army regulations prevent them from leaving 
the compound except for officially organized excursions to sights 
like berlins world war ii memorials 
a cocoon of soviet life is spun around the grim encampment from 
the framed photographs of soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev 
hanging over the rows of cots to the barracks reading rooms stocked 
with communist party literature and political works by sanctioned 
soviet writers 
soldiers said they are allowed to send home two letters per week 
and mail boxes are bolted to the wall at the barracks entrance one 
for letters and the other for letters that have already been 
read 
col alexander kireyev head of the base political department 
described the second letter drop as a sort of diplomatic pouch to 
protect official communications posters adorning the walls warn 
the soldiers to guard against unwitting disclosure of military 
secrets 
the mess hall favors russian dishes like fried cabbage borsch 
and solyanka a spicy broth afloat with fatty sausage and pickled 
vegetables 
entertainment according to soldiers like oleg tarabychkin of 
kiev is a free hour to write home or a night at the base movie 
theater 
for the enlisted men its a lonely life they serve twoyear 
terms with no home leaves and their families must remain behind 
the soviet base like others abroad employs no local workers and 
the only women on the site are the wives of their commanding 
officers 
the weaponry under the control of the vislensky regiment has 
been dismissed by western officials as outmoded nato has contended 
its removal will make little difference in the balance of forces 
between east and west 
but the chief of staff for soviet forces in east germany lt 
col valery i fursin claimed the t64 tanks antiaircraft guns 
tactical missiles and other arms to be withdrawn are modern and a 
significant sacrifice 
we have always contended we have parity with the west he 
replied when asked how the reductions would affect the conventional 
weapons balance 
the cutback of soviet forces from east germany czechoslovakia 
hungary and poland was announced by gorbachev last december in a 
speech to the united nations western experts estimate the kremlin 
has 500000 soldiers in eastern europe so the withdrawal is 
expected to reduce that force by about 10 percent yet still remain 
numerically stronger than nato 
the 94 tanks stationed with the vislensky regiment were having 
their guns removed in preparation for the return to soviet 
territory on flatbed train cars that is to begin heading east on 
may 17 
