<TEXT>
ten governors have urged energy secretary james d watkins to 
set a national policy for cleaning up radioactive and hazardous 
waste at the nations nuclear defense plants within 30 years 
the cleanup and disposal of defense wastes has been 
deferred too long the governors said in the cover letter to a 
sevenpage report they delivered to watkins friday 
the defense waste problem is national in its scope and 
severity the letter said its resolution is a national 
obligation it must also be a national priority 
each of the governors has a doe research or defense facility in 
his state the proposal requests the setting of a firm timetable 
for cleaning up all doe sites within 30 years and creation of a 
trust fund to guarantee adequate resources to complete the job 
without a firm schedule there is no assurance that the 
critical cleanup work will be completed in a timely manner if at 
all the report said we feel that a commitment to clean up all 
facilities within 30 years is both essential and achievable 
the federal government has estimated defense waste cleanup will 
cost between 110 billion and 130 billion over the next 50 years 
less than 1 billion was authorized in the current federal budget 
mainly for waste management and temporary storage rather than 
cleanup and permanent disposal 
the competition for funds between production and cleanup 
activities must end the report said funding priorities for 
cleanup must be driven by the risks posed by waste problems and not 
the need to maintain production operations 
the paper was signed by govs ned ray mcwherter of tennessee 
richard celeste of ohio booth gardner of washington cecil andrus 
of idaho carroll campbell of south carolina garrey carruthers of 
new mexico roy romer of colorado bob miller of nevada neil 
goldschmidt of oregon and wallace wilkinson of kentucky 
