<TEXT>
mob violence that has cost the lives of 
hundreds of senegalese and mauritanians in each others countries 
is rooted in the ancient conflict of nomad and farmer and in the 
river that is a lifeline for both 
long before a country named senegal existed before the enormous 
colony called french west africa was created the black toucouleur 
people farmed the fertile basin on both sides of the senegal river 
arabberber people known as moors living to the north in what 
became mauritania were proud wanderers herders of camels and 
goats who had no interest in a sedentary life on the land 
when the french left and the two nations were created the river 
became their border 
dams have made the basin more valuable attracting moorish 
investors senegalese are being forced from land their forebears 
tilled and new restrictions are being applied to what once was 
relatively free crossborder grazing mostly by mauritanian herds 
in diawara a riverbank village a burst of gunfire april 9 
killed two senegalese farmers some say mauritanian border guards 
did the shooting others say mauritanian tribesmen 
the incident inspired a spree of reprisal lootings beatings and 
killings in many areas of both countries particularly the 
capitals dakar in senegal and nouakchott in mauritania 
neither government has given casualty figures unofficial counts 
indicate about 60 people were killed in senegal and 200 in 
mauritania and that thousands were wounded 
so bad did the violence become that senegal and mauritania 
organized an air shuttle to bring their expatriates home france 
algeria morocco and spain contributed planes 
