<TEXT>
the oliver north trial had been in progress 
for more than two months and his name had been woven through the 
testimony like thread through cloth when north finally was called 
to the stand 
so youre colonel north said his lawyer 
yes sir said north with a tight smile 
its traditional to start with your full name prompted his 
lawyer brendan sullivan 
oliver laurence withau north said the defendant 
so began six days of questioning in which the 45yearold north 
tried to convince his jury that he was unjustly charged that the 
crimes laid to his feet had honorable roots that his motives were 
righteous and that his actions carried out the wishes of none other 
than the president of the united states 
that he largely succeeded was borne out by thursdays verdict 
which seemed to signal the jurys belief he should be punished only 
for those things in which he had total control nobody ordered 
north to accept an illegal gift the security fence around his 
home and nobody ordered him to mutilate documents that would 
expose his machinations 
did you intend to violate any law by receiving the security 
system without paying for it asked sullivan 
no i intended to pay for it 
but did you ever pay for it 
no i did not said north 
even on the third conviction creating false chronologies of the 
irancontra affair for congress the jury found only that he 
aided and abetted not that he was the principal in that 
charge too altering and shredding documents was an element north 
had testified that one of his bosses former national security 
adviser robert mcfarlane had ordered the doctored version 
mcfarlane said it wasnt so 
the oliver north on the witness stand was not the oliver north 
seen by millions on television who told congress i did a lot of 
things and i want to stand up and say im proud of them neither 
was he the oliver north of last weeks television fiction who so 
idolized powerful men that he wound up as everybodys patsy 
after two years under the irancontra cloud north had changed 
the boyish brown hair had grayed his passionate patriotism hadnt 
dimmed but in court it was muted he was being talked about as if 
he had left the room and north reacted by busying himself taking 
miles of notes with his left hand he still knew who the enemy was 
four days in a row prosecutor john keker said good morning mr 
north and the witness pointedly remained mute 
the six rows of ribbons silver star for conspicuous gallantry 
bronze star marked with v for valor for heroism purple heart for 
being twice wounded in action had given way to dark suits and 
ultraconservative ties there was nothing either to replace the 
presidential service badge that had adorned his right breast in 
1987 
the jury got to know more about north through his own testimony 
than through the testimony of others 
how many engagements with the enemy would you have encountered 
during your time in vietnam asked sullivan 
oh i dont know that i never really kept track north 
replied roughly 100 i would suppose 
he said that when congress passed the boland amendment in 1984 
forbidding military aid to the guerrillas fighting nicaraguas 
leftist government it was clear that they wanted to find some 
way of continuing the support they being the white house 
the cia he said had been providing everything from the 
little tents that they lived in to the homes that they had for 
their children to the food they ate the weapons they carried the 
bullets they had everything had come form the cia all of the 
intelligence all of the operations planning 
q what did you understand your assignment to be 
a i understood it very clearly to be that i would be the one to 
replace the cia for each of these activities 
but what about the boland amendment i talked to director 
casey i talked to mr mcfarlane i talked to the nsc lawyers 
none of them thought that it applied to the nsc 
</TEXT>
