the official who asked not to be identified said there are no 
reliable figures on the amount of these assets but they are 
believed to be in the hundreds of millions of dollars 
noriega was indicted last year by two florida grand juries on 
drug smuggling charges 
for more than a week there has been a steady drumbeat of 
administration allegations that noriega has been laying the 
groundwork for a rigged process aimed at ensuring victory for his 
handpicked presidential candidate carlos duque 
on friday state department spokeswoman margaret tutwiler 
expressed suspicion about a huge increase in the 
officiallyannounced numbers of registered voters over the past 
five years suggesting that the figures were falsified 
panamanian authorities meanwhile have been accusing the united 
states of meddling in the election seizing on published reports 
that the administration secretly provided 10 million to the 
opposition coalition 
the reagan administration imposed a series of sanctions against 
panama last year after noriega and his allies ousted president eric 
arturo delvalle among other actions 50 million in panamanian 
government assets in the united states were frozen 
the united states continues to recognize delvalle as the 
legitimate authority in panama and has said there can be no 
normalization of relations with any panamanian government dominated 
by noriega 
the officials cautioned that no concrete decisions have been 
made on future punitive action if as expected a fraudulent 
election is held 
over the medium term one decision that will be forced on the 
administration concerns the appointment for the first time of a 
panamanian as administrator of the panama canal commission which 
is responsible for running the waterway 
the canal treaties specify that panama later this year will 
nominate a candidate to head the commission subject to us 
approval and senate confirmation 
the nominee would take office next year but would be subject to 
policy guidelines issued by the canals board of directors where 
us members are in the majority 
the official said his personal view is that the administration 
will not accept a norieganominated candidate but the final 
decision on that issue has not yet been made 
if the us refuses to allow a panamanian to lead the 
commission this could leave the administration open to charges of 
violating the canal treaties for the time being however the 
administration position is that it has every intention of abiding 
by the terms of the treaty 
noriega a 52yearold ustrained military man has gone from 
a favorite of us antidrug and intelligence agencies to an 
outcast whom the us now accuses of corruption drug trafficking 
and internal repression 
noriega was intelligence chief under the late dictator omar 
torrijos and as such collaborated with us agencies for years 
like torrijos he has maintained contacts with latin governments 
and military leaders not too friendly to the united states 
his backers maintain the united states would have been better 
advised to work with noriega in exploiting those ties than trying 
to oust him 
the us government has acted in a very stupid manner maj 
edgardo lopez a spokesman for noriega said recently in panama 
city the drug charge against noriega is a cover the us does 
not care about drugs if it did it would fight consumption at home 
they want noriega out because he opposed an invasion of nicaragua 
and the training of contras in panama and because he opposes plans 
by the united states to keep its forces here beyond the year 2000 
besides freezing panamanian government funds in the united 
