schooners here eventually the 68foot twomasted glenn l 
swetman will be joined by a second asyetunnamed schooner 
in the late 19th and early 20th centuries the schooners 
harvested gulf shrimp and oysters and raced one another in the 
offseasons 
both the seafood title and the fishing fleets became victims of 
change when motorized boats began scooping up a depleting bounty 
and schooners largely disappeared by the 1930s 
the glenn l swetman wont be scooping up shrimp and oysters 
but it will race and earn its keep as a charter and educational 
boat 
the schooner project begun in 1986 and a seafood industry 
museum are part of an effort to revive the biloxi waterfront 
now this is true progress with preservation bringing back 
historic boats as a symbol of our revival said biloxi mayor 
gerald blessey as he watched the schooner slip into the water we 
are already getting requests for charters for this boat even for 
convention parties 
numerous fundraisers private contributions and an 80000 bank 
loan have footed the bill for the 200000 schooner 
